comments:
Compared with some other societies, we are not very future-oriented (e.g. Project GLOBE values), so it's not too surprising that we as a country didn't take this very seriously till it was right on top of us. On the other hand, China is future-oriented, and it caught them off guard too.

I just wonder what will happen -- all the way from the individual level of analysis to the world level. I do think this will end up being some sort of line of cultural demarcation, where we think in terms of pre- and post-COVID-19. We have had enormously influential events happen, but not anything ongoing with such great effect since WWII. So much remains unknown.

comments:
I wish you all well!  My immediate family is scattered in NY, CA, Scotland and extended family and life long friends in NJ, & NC, so there are a lot of places to follow the news!  

When I first read about the coronavirus in mid January I immediately packed a "go-bag" of essentials.  This concept is based on an experience I had in 1971/72, when caught up in the Indo-Pakistani war zone for three weeks. What is critical and able to be carried on foot? Years later I added to that a surprise river flood caused by an ice jam in 1981 and a house fire in 1993.  Preparation is essential, be ready to move fast.  I purchased a six week supply of foods, etc over the course of time since mid-January. 

I immediately started a twitter list of profs, docs, medical journos, and health depts. Family and friends can tune in, they have the link. I retweet selections from this list. In addition I send email alerts based on news and research.  Everyone in my circle is, for the most part, locked down, self isolating and supplied with 6 weeks of stuff.

Of course, this will not be enough!  I expect conditions to become far worse but there's always the possibility of a break through in medication.  I follow a bunch of Scientist heros!  Just hope the internet stays up.  The folks in my circle included those with disabilities and several aged 70-75 years, the youngest is 3 years old.  I do not expect we all will make it through to the other side, but that's okay, too.  You do what you can, hope for the best.  Staying informed in strength, gives one a measure of equilibrium.
